can you still eat sushi when your pregnant if so what kind im weeks prego and i want sushi so bad can i still eat it if so what kind ps my fav is flying fish roll avacodo roll can i still eat it mature answers some types of sushi such as california rolls which contain steamed crab and cooked eel are fine to eat while you're pregnant but it's best to avoid eating the kinds that contain raw seafood such as tuna fresh raw seafood is potentially risky because it can contain parasites such as tapeworm which if they grow large enough could rob your body of nutrients needed for your growing baby freezing and cooking deep sixes the parasites for this reason many japanese restaurants that specialize in sushi use frozen rather than fresh fish but restaurants in the united states aren't required to freeze fish before serving it raw unfortunately one concern about seafood raw or cooked is pcb and chemical contamination if you want to eat fish during your pregnancy contact your local health department or office of the environmental protection agency epa for a list of fish in your area that haven't been contaminated with toxins as a general rule ocean fish such as tuna sea bass sole flounder and snapper are safer than river and lake varieties when eating out at any restaurant order your fish well cooked many upscale eateries lightly sear fresh fish on the outside then serve it rare in both the united states and japan many more people get sick from eating fish served at home than from eating fish at sushi restaurants for seafood safety at home the food and drug administration has a few tips according to the fda's food code you should cook most seafood to an internal temperature of degrees farenheit degrees celsius for seconds if you don't have a thermometer the guidelines listed below can help you to determine whether seafood is done for fish slip the point of a sharp knife into the flesh and pull aside the edges should be opaque and the center slightly translucent with flakes beginning to separate let the fish stand three to four minutes to finish cooking shrimp and lobster turn red when cooked the flesh becomes pearly opaque scallops appear milky white or opaque and firm for clams mussels and oysters watch for the point at which their shells open which indicates that they're done throw out those that remain closed after cooking when microwaving seafood rotate the dish several times to ensure even cooking after letting the dish stand check seafood in several spots with a thermometer to see if it's reached the proper temperature http www babycenter com expert pregnancy pregnancynutrition html Foodborne illness Cuisine of Singapore Vegetarianism Salmon Kosher foods Tofu Cantonese cuisine Cuisine of Denmark French cuisine German cuisine Veganism Fish and chips Lobster Oyster RuneScape skills Cuisine of the Philippines Healthy eating Kashrut Fugu Pizza Fishery Kitchen Mercury (element) Egg (food) Sashimi Taboo food and drink Cajun cuisine Cheese Dim sum Ramen Vitamin C Cuisine of Africa Restaurant Food Conveyor belt sushi Cuisine of Malaysia Tea Hamburger Water (molecule) Sewage treatment Shark Escherichia coli O157:H7 Hot pot Roman eating and drinking Breastfeeding French fries Organic farming Breakfast Raw food diet Seafood Fish farming Tempura Barbecue Antarctic krill Tlingit Polychlorinated biphenyl Taiwanese cuisine Chinese cuisine Cuisine of the Southern United States Bengali cuisine Meat Domesticated turkey Cuisine of Brazil Coffee Toxoplasmosis Temperature Dog Knife Agriculture Peruvian cuisine Fish Water 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake Solar power Folic acid Curry Angling Hand grenade Unclean animals Fauna of Australia Bento Mussel USS Tunny (SS-282) Krill Dialysis Halaal Wasabi Banana Milk 